der Occupation: The City of Donetsk -- tCitizens without Citizenship -- tHomo Donbasus, or The Changes Brought by the War -- tAbout Easter… and More -- tChaos in Their Heads: How the War Is Perceived in the Occupied Zone -- tWhat Pygmalion Left Unsaid -- tEvening Strolls through an Empty City -- tQuid Prodest? -- tThe “Remainers”: The Undiscovered Bosch of the DPR -- tScreeching in the Thorns -- t“Primaries” under the Occupation -- tPropaganda on the Streets of Donetsk -- tOccupation as It Is: Khartsyzk -- tThat Sweet Word, “War” -- tWhere the Elite of Occupied Donetsk Take Their Leisure -- tDonetsk: A Tour of Expropriated Places -- tImmersed in War -- tThe Donbas in 2017: Three Variations on a Theme -- tThe DPR and Religion -- tHow the Militants Prepare Children to Join Their Military Organizations -- t“I Fought in the War”: Life after Leaving the DPR Militia -- tBack in the USSR: Soviet Themes in Donetsk Eateries -- t“Looking for a Tusk to Buy”: Ads in Occupied Donetsk -- tFollowing the Path of Crimea? -- tUs and Them -- tA Knack for Losing Things -- tNotes -- tIllustration Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this exceptional collection of dispatches from occupied Donbas, writer and journalist Stanislav Aseyev details the internal and external changes observed in the cities of Makiïvka and Donetsk in eastern Ukraine. Aseyev scrutinizes his immediate environment and questions himself in an attempt to understand the reasons behind the success of Russian propaganda among the working-class residents of the industrial region of Donbas. In this work of documentary prose, Aseyev focuses on the early period of the Russian-sponsored military aggression in Ukraine’s east, the period of 2015–2017. The author’s testimony ends with his arrest for publishing his dispatches and his subsequent imprisonment and torture in a modern-day concentration camp on the outskirts of Donetsk run by lawless mercenaries and local militants with the tacit approval and support of Moscow. For the first time, an inside account is presented here of the toll on real human lives and civic freedoms that the citizens of Europe’s largest country continue to suffer in Russia’s hybrid war on its territory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aUkraine Conflict, 2014-vPersonal narratives. 0aUkraine Conflict, 2014-xOccupied territories. 70(DE-588)4020517-40(DE-627)1063177680(DE-576)208933697aGeschichte2gnd 70(DE-588)4113450-30(DE-627)1058293900(DE-576)209476583aEntwicklung2gnd 70(DE-588)4129821-40(DE-627)1045404510(DE-576)209613726aInvasion2gnd 70(DE-588)7514383-50(DE-627)5010093880(DE-576)253338301aKonfliktlinie2gnd 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / European / Eastern (see also Russian & Former Soviet Union).2bisacsh1 aWolanskyj, Lidia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311078579140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674268807?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674268807423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674268807/original  a978-3-11-078579-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099375-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studie